Russell's viper┬а(Daboia russelii) is a┬аspecies┬аof┬аvenomous snake┬аin the┬аfamily┬аViperidae of venomous┬аOld World┬аvipers. It is found in┬аAsia┬аthroughout the┬аIndian subcontinent, much of┬аSoutheast Asia, southern┬аChina┬аand┬аTaiwan.┬аThe species is named for┬аPatrick Russell┬а(1726тАУ1805), a┬аScottish┬аherpetologist┬аwho first described many of┬аIndia's snakes, and the name of the genus is from the┬аHindi┬аword meaning "that lies hid", or "the lurker". In┬аBengali┬аthis snake is called┬аchandroborha┬аsince it carries lenticular or more precisely lunar marks all over its body. In┬аMarathi┬аthis snake is called┬аGhonas. Apart from being a member of the┬аbig four┬аsnakes in India,┬аDaboia┬аis also one of the genera responsible for causing the most┬аsnakebite┬аincidents and deaths among all venomous snakes on account of many factors, such as their wide distribution, generally aggressive demeanor, and frequent occurrence in highly populated areas.

Daboia russelli┬аis commonly known as┬аRussell's viper┬аand┬аchain viper, among other names.

DescriptionEdit

я┐╝



D. russelii┬аcan grow to a maximum length (body + tail) of 166┬аcm (5.5┬аft) and averages about 120┬аcm (4┬аft) on mainland Asian populations. Island populations may be slightly smaller on average.┬аIt is more slender than most vipers.┬аDitmars┬а(1937) reported the following dimensions for a "fair-sized adult specimen":

Total length4┬аft., 1┬аinch124┬аcmLength of tail:7┬аinches18┬аcm Girth:6┬аinches15┬аcm Width of head2┬аinches5┬аcmLength of head2┬аinches5┬аcm


я┐╝

Russell's viper from the wild

The head is flattened, triangular, and distinct from the neck. The snout is blunt, rounded, and raised. The nostrils are large, each in the middle of a large, single┬аnasal scale. The lower edge of the nasal scale touches the┬аnasorostral┬аscale. The supranasal scale has a strong crescent shape and separates the nasal from the nasorostral scale anteriorly. The┬аrostral scale┬аis as broad as it is high.[6]

я┐╝

Head of the Russell's viper

The crown of the head is covered with irregular, strongly fragmented scales. The┬аsupraocular scales┬аare narrow, single, and separated by six to nine scales across the head. The eyes are large, flecked with yellow or gold, and surrounded by 10тАУ15┬аcircumorbital scales. The snake has 10тАУ12┬аsupralabials, the fourth and fifth of which are significantly larger. The eye is separated from the supralabials by three or four rows of┬аsuboculars. Of the two pairs of┬аchin shields, the front pair is notably enlarged. The two maxillary bones support at least two and at the most five or six pairs of fangs at a time: the first are active and the rest replacements.[6]┬аThe fangs attain a length of 16.5┬аmm (0.65┬аin) in the average specimen.[10]

я┐╝

The body is stout, the cross-section of which is rounded to circular. The┬аdorsal scales┬аare strongly┬аkeeled; only the lowest row is smooth. Mid-body, the dorsal scales number 27тАУ33. The┬аventral scales┬аnumber 153тАУ180. The┬аanal plate┬аis not divided. The tail is short тАФ about 14% of the total length тАФ with the paired┬аsubcaudals┬аnumbering 41тАУ68.[6]

Dorsally, the color pattern consists of a deep yellow, tan, or brown ground color, with three series of dark brown spots that run the length of the body. Each of these spots has a black ring around it, the outer border of which is intensified with a rim of white or yellow. The dorsal spots, which usually number 23тАУ30, may grow together, while the side spots may break apart. The head has a pair of distinct dark patches, one on each temple, together with a pinkish, salmon, or brownish V or X marking that forms an apex towards the snout. Behind the eye is a dark streak, outlined in white, pink, or buff. The┬аventer┬аis white, whitish, yellowish, or pinkish, often with an irregular scattering of dark spots.
